			      <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				        <p>On the 7th day of the … in year 20 … Māṭharīputta
					Siri-Vīrapurisadatta, (son) of the Great King Siri-Cāntamūla
					— sacrificer of the Aśvamedha, giver of numerous tens of
					millions of [pieces of] gold, (hundreds of thousands of cows
					and hundreds of thousands of plows of land) —, who increased
					…, whose commands were received on the head by [kings of?]
					Tosala, Kosala, Paṭu, and Magadha, the overlord of the
					Viñjha (Vindhya) mountain ... and Siripavvata (Śrīparvata),
					who has obtained majesty ... in many battles — this image has
					been established.</p>
			      </div>
			      <div type="commentary">
				        <listApp>
					          <app loc="3">
						            <note>Our translation is based on the assumption that
							the word <foreign xml:lang="pra-Brah">putasa</foreign> has been lost in the lacuna at
							the end of this line.</note>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="4">
						            <lem>k<unclear>a</unclear>mal<gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="aksarapart"/>
						            </lem>
						            <note>This first epithet is at present obscure to us.
							<!--Perhaps vāsaka is the end of °uvāsaka (AG)?--></note>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="4–5">
						            <lem>
							              <supplied reason="lost">to</supplied>salakosalapaṭuma<unclear>gha</unclear>dhi-</lem>
						            <note>This compound is composed of four place-names, the
							first two of which form a pair commonly encountered
							in the literature, and discussed at length in <bibl>
                        <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Lévi1923"/>:
								<citedRange>1–11</citedRange>
                     </bibl>. The third toponym, <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">paṭu</foreign>, is more
							obscure, but the <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">paṭavas</foreign> or people of Paṭu feature in
							Purāṇic lists of people living in the Vindhyas (cf. <bibl>
								                <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Sircar1971"/>:
									<citedRange>44</citedRange>
							              </bibl>). Their exact location is uncertain.
							Finally, <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">maghadhi</foreign> seems to point to the
							inhabitants of Magadha, where the aspiration of the
							final consonant seems to have been imposed also on
							the second one. The form <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">maghada</foreign> with full
							inversion of aspiration is encountered in the
							manuscript tradition of the Śaktisaṅgamatantra, as
							noted in <bibl>
								                <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Sircar1971"/>:
									<citedRange>85</citedRange>
							              </bibl>.</note>
						            <!--The form maghadha occurs also twice in Tripathi’s edition of the Br̥hatsaṃhitā 11:55 and 32:11. I don’t have the edition at hand and that of Bhatt has the regular magadha (VT)-->
					          </app>
					          <app loc="5–6">
						            <lem>-sira<unclear>sā</unclear>
							              <supplied reason="lost">saṁpaṭi</supplied>chitasāsanasa</lem>
						            <note>Our reconstruction here is informed by the
							occurrence of the phrase <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">sirasā
								saṁpaṭicchitasāsana</foreign>, meaning “whose
							rule/teaching has been accepted by [the bowing
							of] the head” in Pali commentarial literature. See
							Dīghanikāyaṭṭhakathāṭikā (ed. De Silva 1970) III 158.4–5: <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">gahetabbavacano sirasā
								sampaṭicchitasāsano</foreign>; Paramatthadīpanī (ed. Bose 1934–36) I 78.8–10: <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">evaṁmahānubhāvo ti cakkaratanādisamannāgamena
								kassaci pi pīḷaṁ akaronto va sabbarājūhi sirasā
								sampaṭicchitasāsanavehāsagamanādīhi evaṁ
								mahānubhāvo</foreign>.<!--Alternatively, one could also imagine a reconstruction *<foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">anatichitasāsana</foreign> (≈ <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">anatītaśāsana</foreign>)—cf. Vogel’s (1929-30) explanation of <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">atichita</foreign>- in the Nagarjunakonda inscriptions—but we consider this option less convincing, and anyhow it is unsupported by external evidence.--></note>
