                  <note>However we reconstruct this compound, it is clear that it offers an interesting antecedent to royal epithets bore by Viṣṇukuṇḍin rulers and Pr̥thivīśrīmūla. See, for instance, EIAD <ref target="#EIAD0181">181</ref>, l. 5: <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">cānekacāturddantasamaraśatasahasrasaṅghaṭṭavijayī</foreign>; <ref target="#EIAD0186">186</ref>, st. II: <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">bahusamarajayopāttonatataśrīr</foreign>; <ref target="#EIAD0189">189</ref>, ll. 7–9: <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">°asakr̥danekaniśitanistriṁśasahasrasaṁkulātibhīmasaṁgrāmabhūmipratilabdhavijayī</foreign>. This feat of king Vīrapurisadatta is also likely hinted at in one of the two narrative reliefs preserved on the pillar itself, which shows the ruler riding an elephant and accompanied by soldiers.</note>
